{"title_page": "Charles Ethelston", "text_new": "[[File:The political house that Jack built (1819) (14750648056).jpg|thumb|Political caricature from 1819, the central figure with the staff intended as Charles Ethelston]]\n'''Charles Wickstead Ethelston''', also given as '''Wicksted''' (1767\u20131830) was an English cleric, now remembered for the part he played in his role as magistrate on 16 August 1819, ahead of the [[Peterloo massacre]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the son of the Rev. Charles Ethelstone (1731\u20131795), an Oxford graduate, and his wife Margaret Hart (died 1803) of [[Salford]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Admission Register of the Manchester School |publisher=Manchester University Press |pages=4-5 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HAYNAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA4 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Ethelstone, Charles}}</ref><ref>{{CCEd |type=person |id=26866 |name=Ethelstone, Charles |year1=1754 |year2=1795 |accessed=18 March 2020}}</ref> He was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]] under Charles Lawson, and matriculated at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] in 1787, graduating B.A. in 1790 and M.A. in 1793.<ref name=\"acad\">{{acad|id=ETLN785CW|name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted}}</ref> He was known also by the surnames Ethelstone and Ethelstane.\n\nEthelston became a curate in 1794 at St Mark's Chapel, [[Cheetham Hill]], which was then an urbanising area adjacent to Manchester and [[Salford]].<ref name=\"CCEd\">{{CCEd |type=person |id=168787 |name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted |year1=1790 |year2=1831 |accessed=18 March 2020 }}</ref> His father, who died the following year, had recently completed it, at his own expense, on the Shooting Butts field at Cheetham;<ref name=\"Stancliffe\">{{cite book |last1=Stancliffe |first1=F. S. |title=The Manchester Royal Eye Hospital |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=5 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cRgNAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA5 |language=en}}</ref> it was a [[chapel of ease]] between the [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Prestwich]] and [[Manchester Collegiate Church]], for which Charles Ethelstone the elder had permission to build in 1790, in a hamlet where cotton merchants lived.<ref name=\"Genuki\">{{cite book |title=Genuki: St Mark Church of England, Cheetham, Lancashire |url=https://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Cheetham/StMark |language=en}}</ref> The chapel was consecrated on 24 July 1794 by [[William Markham]].<ref name=\"Churches\">{{cite web |title=Lancashire OnLine Parish Clerk Project |url=https://www.lan-opc.org.uk/Manchester/Cheetham/churches.html |website=www.lan-opc.org.uk}}</ref> Later, Ethelston became a [[perpetual curate]] there. A Jubilee School was built in Cheetham, and a plot of land obtained from [[Thomas Reynolds-Moreton, 1st Earl of Ducie|Lord Ducie]] to build a church to seat 1500.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lewis |first1=Samuel |title=A Topographical Dictionary of England: Comprising the Several Counties, Cities, Boroughs, Corporate and Market Towns, Parishes, Chapelries, and Townships, and the Islands of Guernsey, Jersey, and Man, with Historical and Statistical Descriptions|date=1840 |publisher=S. Lewis & Company |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iARBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA501 |language=en}}</ref> The church was closed in 1982, and demolished around 1998.<ref name=\"Genuki\"/><ref name=\"Churches\"/>\n\nIn 1801, Ethelston was made rector of [[Worthenbury]], near [[Wrexham]].<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> The presentation was presumably (according to [[Francis Robert Raines]]) by [[Sir Richard Price Puleston, 1st Baronet]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chetham Society |first1=Manchester |title=Remains, historical and literary, connected with the palatine counties of Lancaster and Chester. New ser |date=1883 |publisher=Manchester |page=307 |url=https://archive.org/details/remainshistornew23chetuoft/page/306/mode/2up}}</ref> In 1804 he became a Fellow of Manchester Collegiate Church.<ref name=\"acad\"/>\n[[File:St Mark's Church, Cheetham Hill, 1891.jpg|thumb|St Mark's Church, Cheetham Hill, interior in 1891]]\n\n==Civic Manchester==\nEthelston was chaplain to Silvester's Volunteers, raised in 1803 by John Silvester.<ref name=\"Navickas\">{{cite book |last1=Navickas |first1=Katrina |title=Loyalism and Radicalism in Lancashire, 1798-1815 |date=2009 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-955967-1 |page=121 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xYUDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA121 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Timperley |first1=Charles Henry |title=Records historical, municipal |date=1874 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YA4HAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA67 |language=en}}</ref> Silvester was a millowner and magistrate, and the volunteer unit, the 2nd Regiment of the Manchester and Salford Rifle Volunteers, was active against [[Luddites]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Philp |first1=Mark |title=Resisting Napoleon: The British Response to the Threat of Invasion, 1797\u20131815 |date=2016 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-351-90385-1 |page=65 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DamoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT65 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nFor the Golden Jubilee of [[George III]], celebrated on 25 October 1809, Ethelston addressed in the Collegiate Church John Ratliff the boroughreeve and his constables, joined by the Masonic Lodge and the Orange Order. There was a procession on to [[St Ann's Square, Manchester|St Ann's Square]], joyshots from dragoons and a volley from the rifle brigade. A loyal toast was drunk, and dinner for around 250 eaten at the [[Manchester Cotton Exchange]]. Nearly 800 children from the [[Lancasterian school]] lined Lever Street.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Tradesman |date=1809 |pages=532-533 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9C4aAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA532 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812, Ethelston and Silvester were among a group of loyalists intending to hold a dinner in the Exchange, with a toast and pledge to the [[Prince Regent]]. It was frustrated by an occupation of the Exchange, that led to vandalism.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Phythian |first1=Graham |title=Peterloo: Voices, Sabres and Silence |date=2018 |publisher=History Press |isbn=978-0-7509-8951-0 |page=46 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hA5dDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT46 |language=en}}</ref> In 1814 Ethelston was a founding board member of [[Manchester Royal Eye Hospital]].<ref name=\"Stancliffe\"/>\n\n==Magistrate==\nClerical magistrates were common in England in the later 18th century and early 19th century. Their numbers dropped back after 1832 and the [[Great Reform Act]]: in 1740 they were uncommon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hole |first1=Robert |title=Pulpits, Politics and Public Order in England, 1760-1832 |date=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-89365-7 |edition=186 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8du3_4Q5V8AC&pg=PA186 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibson |first1=William |title=Church, State and Society, 1760\u20131850 |date=1994 |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education |isbn=978-1-349-23204-8 |page=13 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkpdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13 |language=en}}</ref> In [[Lancashire]] the custom was to exclude manufacturers from the bench, to keep it impartial in trade disputes: the practical result was that it was dominated by landowners and clerics, and by [[High Church]] and [[High Tory]] views. In Manchester at this period the prominent magistrates, according to Marlow, were the lawyer [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]], and two clerics, Ethelston and William Robert Hay.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |page=49 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs a magistrate, Ethelston employed informers and spies, passing information about possible subversion to the [[Home Office]]. The Home Office funded spies in industrial districts: for Ethelston and Hay, and also Ralph Fletcher, magistrate at [[Bolton]], John Lloyd who was a magistrate's clerk at [[Stockport]], and Henry Enfield, town clerk of [[Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The Town Labourer, 1760-1832; the new civilization |date=1917 |publisher=London, Longmans, Green |page=258|volume=1 |url=https://archive.org/details/townlabourer00hammuoft/page/258/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Turner |first1=Bernadette |title=A Loyal Englishman?: John Lloyd and Aspects of Oath-taking in 1812 |url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1057/9780230509382_9 |website=Radicalism and Revolution in Britain, 1775\u20131848: Essays in Honour of Malcolm I. Thomis |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK |pages=133\u2013142 |language=en |doi=10.1057/9780230509382_9 |date=2000}}</ref> In 1816 Ethelston was encouraged by [[John Hiley Addington]], at the Home Office as parliamentary secretary to his brother [[Lord Sidmouth]], to employ spies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Reid |first1=Robert |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=2017 |publisher=Random House |isbn=978-1-4735-5477-1 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QBcqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT45 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Riding |first1=Jacqueline |title=Peterloo: The Story of the Manchester Massacre |date=2018 |publisher=Head of Zeus Ltd |isbn=978-1-78669-582-6 |page=69 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ydVADwAAQBAJ&pg=PT69 |language=en}}</ref> Ethelston, Fletcher and Hay had in common membership of the [[Loyal Orange Institution]].<ref name=\"Navickas\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Neal |first1=Frank |title=Sectarian Violence: The Liverpool Experience, 1819-1914 : an Aspect of Anglo-Irish History |date=1988 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-1483-3 |page=19 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EqfnAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA19 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nEthelston had some success in 1817, when he sent Samuel Fleming and another spy into Yorkshire, to look for [[pike (weapon)|pike]]s being stored.<ref name=\"Hammonds\">{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The Town Labourer, 1760-1832; the new civilization |date=1917 |publisher=London, Longmans, Green |pages=260-261 |url=https://archive.org/details/townlabourer00hammuoft/page/260/mode/2up}}</ref> Fleming was an Irish weaver who had served in Silvester's Volunteers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Michael T. |last2=Macleod |first2=Emma |last3=Pentland |first3=Gordon |title=Political Trials in an Age of Revolutions: Britain and the North Atlantic, 1793\u20141848 |date=2018 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-3-319-98959-4 |page=198 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j_CBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA198 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1818 Ethelston clashed with and abused Thomas Chapman, proprietor of the ''[[Manchester Observer]]'', at a vestry meeting of the Manchester parish. Chapman was concerned with the oversight of the accounts of the local constables.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=The Manchester Observer: Biography of a Radical Newspaper |journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library |date=1 March 2019 |volume=95 |issue=1 |pages=31\u2013123, at pp. 46-47 |doi=10.7227/BJRL.95.1.3 |url=http://clok.uclan.ac.uk/28037/1/28037.pdf}}</ref> In 1818 also, during the weavers' strike, the magistrates Ethelston, Norris, William Marriott, and Ralph Wright pre-empted a planned meeting of weavers on 4 September, at Ashton Cross, [[Tameside]], with a notice that such assemblies of the unemployed were a danger to the public peace.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The skilled labourer, 1760-1832 |date=1919 |publisher=London, New York [etc.] : Longmans, Green and co. |page=116 |url=https://archive.org/details/skilledlabourer00hammiala/page/116/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n===Events of 1819===\nSubsequently Ethelston's credibility with the Home Office dropped. He wrote to Lord Sidmouth in June 1819 of an intended \"general rising\".<ref>Robert Poole, \"By the Law or the Sword\": Peterloo Revisited'', History Vol. 91, No. 2 (302) (April 2006), pp. 254\u2013276, at p. 265\u2013266. Published by: Wiley {{jstor|24427836}}</ref> Fleming had fed him a report that [[William Cobbett]]'s visit to Lancashire was the signal for such a rising.<ref name=\"Hammonds\"/> His spy John Livesey tried to make direct contact with Sidmouth in London during 1819, claiming Ethelston had directed him to do so.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bend |first1=Nathan Ashley |title=The Home Office and Public Disturbance, c.1800-1832 |date=2018 |pge=105 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/27d9/3b2be3a1cb1820c00927156e5d56a60dd0b1.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Making of the English Working Class]]'', [[E. P. Thompson]] wrote of summer 1819 that \"The government wanted blood \u2014 not a holocaust, but enough to make an example.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=Edward Palmer |title=The Making of the English Working Class |date=1980 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0140136037 |page=723 |language=en}}</ref> In the historiography of Peterloo, however, Thompson's thesis from 1963, in the form that the Home Office deliberately triggered violence against the meeting in [[St Peter's Square, Manchester|St Peter's Field]], has been challenged.<ref name=\"Read\">Donald Read, ''Reviewed Work: Peterloo: The Case Reopened by Robert Walmsley'', History Vol. 55, No. 183 (1970), pp. 138\u2013140. Published by: Wiley {{jstor|24406795}}</ref> \n\nCorrespondence of the Home Office with Lancashire magistrates was through [[Henry Hobhouse (archivist)|Henry Hobhouse]], under-secretary of state from 1817 to 1827. He made it clear that the magistrates should set their house in order. In January 1819 he used a phrase about blood \"shed either by the Law or the sword\", prompted by a letter from Ralph Fletcher.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: The English Uprising |date=2019 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-878346-6 |page=211 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q5ygDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA211 |language=en}}</ref> On 23 July the Select Committee of Lancashire and Cheshire Magistrates was formed, and its first act was to lay a case of [[seditious libel]] against [[James Wroe]], editor of the ''Manchester Observer''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |page=111 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===16 August 1819, Peterloo===\n{{main|Peterloo Massacre}}\nThe magistrates most involved with Peterloo were Ethelston, Hay, Hulton and Norris.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Read |first1=Donald |title=Peterloo The Masssacre and its Background |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=75 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JMVRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA75 |language=en}}</ref> The roles of both Ethelston, reader of the [[Riot Act]], and [[William Hulton]] who brought in the militia, were later questioned as part of revisionism applied to Thompson's account.<ref name=\"Read\"/> Marlow argues that the invocation of the Riot Act was a side-issue, the magistrates having power in [[common law]] to disperse crowds.<ref name=\"Marlow\">{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |pages=147\u2013148 |language=en}}</ref>\n \nThe four were present, and Hulton chaired the committee of magistrates. From around 11 am, a group of nearly a dozen Lancashire and Cheshire magistrates were at Edmund Buxton's house on Mount Steet, overlooking St Peter's Field. It included also Ralph Fletcher, William Marriott, John Silvester and Ralph Wright.<ref>Others being the Rev. John Holdsworth Mallory, Robert Fielden, and Thomas Willian Tatton. ''The Tories, and their punishment of the people at the Peterloo meeting: a few words addressed to working men, the electors of Manchester and elsewhere, as to their duty.'' 1868, at p. 5. {{jstor|60216487}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Stanley |first1=Edward |title=Three Accounts of Peterloo |date=2015 |publisher=Manchester University Press |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sHq7AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA3 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe radicals' meeting on St Peter's Field began at 1.40 pm, as [[Henry Hunt (politician)|Henry Hunt]] started to speak. Hulton's committee took two decisions: to arrest leading radicals; and to disperse the crowd. The stentorian Ethelston read the Riot Act from a window in the Mount Street house, at a point between the attempted enforcements of those decisions. Hay gave an account of how Ethelson hung out of the window, and he had stood behind, ready to catch the tails of Ethelston's coat if he had started to topple. It is not clear that Ethelston was heard. Silvester then left the house, and read the Riot Act from a card.<ref name=\"Marlow\"/>\n\nIn the film ''[[Peterloo (film)|Peterloo]]'' by [[Mike Leigh]], Ethelston is played by [[Vincent Franklin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Peterloo (2018) - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4614612/fullcredits}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath of Peterloo===\n[[File:The political house that Jack built (1819) (14587018178).jpg|thumb|left|Caricature of a two-faced clerical magistrate, from 1819, with the right-hand part holding gallows, scourge, blunderbuss and shackles.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hone |first1=William |title=Regency Radical: Selected Writings of William Hone |date=2003 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=978-0-8143-3060-9 |page=423 note 21 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=52XRU9KuL9kC&pg=PA423 |language=en}}</ref>]] \nSome days afterwards, according to a letter published in the ''Manchester Observer'', Ethelston said while preaching that  Peterloo was the will of God.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=426 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA426 |language=en}}</ref> Henry Hunt appeared before the magistrates on 20 August, initially charged with [[high treason]], those on the bench being Sir William Bagshawe, [[John Byng, 1st Earl of Strafford|Sir John Byng]], Ethelston, Ralph Fletcher, William Hulton, William Marriott, James Norris as chairman, Thomas William Tatton, Trafford Trafford, J. Watkins and Richard Wright.<ref>{{cite book |title=Peterloo Massacre, Containing a Faithful Narrative of the Events which Preceded, Accompanied, and Followed the Fatal Sixteenth of August, 1819, on the Area Near St. Peter's Church, Manchester, Including the Proceedings which Took Place at the Inquest at Oldham ... to which is Added, an Accurate List of the Names and Places of Residence of Those who Were Killed, Wounded and Maimed |date=1819 |publisher=publisher not identified |page=28 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AP4xAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA28 |language=en}}</ref> Ethelston became concerned with headgear: radical supporters were wearing white hats, in imitation of Hunt, with green ribbons, and he wrote to Sidmouth about it on 13 September.<ref>James Epstein, ''Understanding the Cap of Liberty: Symbolic Practice and Social Conflict in Early Nineteenth-Century England'', Past & Present No. 122 (Feb., 1989), pp. 75\u2013118, at p. 110. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650952}}</ref>\n\nEthelston defended William Robert Hay in the ''[[Manchester Gazette]]'' on 25 September 1819, complaining of the ''[[ad hominem]]'' attacks made on all those who opposed reformers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=428 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA428 |language=en}}</ref> [[William Benbow]] in his ''Rambler's Magazine'' in 1822 listed \"Hay and Ethelstone\" with disreputable clerics as \"chief agitators\" in Manchester.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Rambler's Magazine: Or, Fashionable Emporium of Polite Literature|date=1822 |publisher=Benbow |page=409 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=r103AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA409 |language=en}}</ref> Satire against clerical magistrates picked on Ethelston.<ref>{{cite book |page=69 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5PiADwAAQBAJ&pg=PA69}}</ref> According to Gibson, \"It took many years for the people to forget that the magistrates who read the Riot Act at the Peterloo d\u00e9b\u00e2cle were Anglican clergy.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibson |first1=William |title=Church, State and Society, 1760\u20131850 |date=1994 |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education |isbn=978-1-349-23204-8 |pages=88-89 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkpdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA88 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Henry Grey Bennet]] asked the radical [[John Shuttleworth (industrialist)|John Shuttleworth]] on 18 November 1819 for information about the magistrates who signed the warrant to arrest Henry Hunt. This request may have prompted the pamphlet ''Manchester Slaughter!'' by \"Old Radical\". It took the form of an unsympathetic review of Ethelston's book of verse from 1803.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=426 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA426 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA significant publication and best-seller of November 1819 was ''The Political House that Jack Built'', a 24-page verse pamphlet parody of ''[[This Is the House That Jack Built]]'', by [[William Hone]], illustrated by [[George Cruikshank]]'s woodcut caricatures.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Ben |title=The Laughter of Triumph: William Hone and the Fight for the Free Press |date=2014 |publisher=Faber & Faber |isbn=978-0-571-31721-9 |pages=289-290 |language=en}}</ref> It contained \"The Clerical Magistrate\" with lines\n\n<poem>If the People were legally Meeting, in quiet\nWould pronouce it, decidedly\u2014''sec. Stat''\u2014a Riot,\nAnd order the Soldiers 'to aid and assist',\nThat is\u2014kill the helpless, who cannot resist.</poem>\n\nThe accompanying cut by Cruikshank is based on Ethelston, and contains internal references to the way Cruikshank depicted [[Lord Castlereagh]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gardner |first1=J. |title=Poetry and Popular Protest: Peterloo, Cato Street and the Queen Caroline Controversy |date=2011 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-0-230-30737-7 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=P-eHDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA57 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Patten |first1=Robert L. |title=George Cruikshank's Life, Times, and Art: 1792-1835 |date=1992 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |isbn=978-0-7188-2872-1 |page=162|volume=1 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Last years==\nEthelston suffered a head injury when the horse of his [[gig (carriage)|gig]] ran away. He resided at addresses west and north of Manchester (see under Family). He died in September 1830, at age 63, and was buried at St Mark's, Cheetham Hill.<ref name=\"acad\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=428 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA428 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''The Suicide with Other Poems'' (1803)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ethelston |first1=Charles Wicksted |title=The Suicide with Other Poems |date=1803 |publisher=Author and Published |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MfY_AQAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Address delivered in the Exchange Room, in Manchester, to a General Meeting convened by the Boroughreeve and Constables, on Wednesday the 11th. of Decr.,1811, for the purpose of Taking into Consideration the Expediency of Founding Schools on the Plan of Dr. Bell'' (Manchester, 1811), against the [[Lancasterian system]].\n*''The Unity of the Church'' (1814), sermon.<ref name=\"Chetham\">{{cite book |last1=Radcliffe |first1=John |last2=Greswell |first2=William Parr |last3=Jones |first3=Thomas |last4=Byrom |first4=John |title=Bibliotheca Chethamensis. Sive Bibliothec\u00e6 Public\u00e6 Mancuniensis ab Humfredo Chetham armigero fundat\u00e6 catalogus exhibens libros in varias classes pro varietate argumenti distributos ... |date=1883|volume=VI |publisher=Mancunii : Excudebat J. Harrop, etc. |pages=118-119 |url=https://archive.org/details/b29004470_0002/page/118/mode/2up/}}</ref> It was attacked by the [[Wesleyan Methodist]] apologist Edward Wesley Hare (1774\u20131818), writing from Liverpool in 1815, in ''The Exclusive Claims of Episcopal Ordination Examined and Rejected'' (1815);<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hare |first1=Edward Wesley |title=The exclusive claims of episcopal ordination examined and rejected, and the Methodist ministry vindicated; in a ser. of letters to C.W. Ethelson: being a reply to his sermon on 'The unity of the Church'. |date=1815 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QTRcAAAAQAAJ |language=en}}</ref> he had been on the Manchester circuit in 1813.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Joseph |title=Hall's circuits and ministers: an alphabetical list of the circuits in Great Britain, with the names of the ministers stationed in each circuit, from 1765 to 1885 : with appendix from 1886-1896 |date=1897 |page=208 |url=https://archive.org/details/28455030.1897.emory.edu/page/n209/mode/2up |language=English}}</ref> Ethelston was defended in the anonymous ''Strictures on Hare's Letters to the Rev. C. Ethelston'' (1815), <ref>{{cite book |title=Strictures on Hare's Letters to the Rev. C. Ethelston, and on the Methodistical Schism, etc |date=1815 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NmljAAAAcAAJ |language=en}}</ref> and Hare returned to the subject in ''A Further Vindication of the Methodist Ministry'' (1816).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hare |first1=Edward Wesley |title=A further vindication of the Methodist Ministry, against the exclusive claims of Episcopal Ordination: in a series of letters, addressed to ... C. W. Ethelston ... occasioned by anonymous strictures on the author's former letters [to him in answer to his sermon on the Unity of the Church], etc |date=1816 |publisher=Roberts & Company |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UQZgAAAAcAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n*''A Patriotic Appeal to the Good Sense of All Parties'' (1817), pseudonymous, as \"An Anti-Jacobin\".<ref name=\"Chetham\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Dicitonary of Anonymous and Pseudonymous English Literature |publisher=Ardent Media |page=312 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Tg0caI1-EToC&pg=PA312 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nEthelston was twice married: firstly to Mary Threlfall, daughter of John Threlfall of [[Chorley]]; and secondly in 1804 to Hannah Edwards, daughter of John Edwards of [[Kelsterton]].<ref name=\"acad\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Aikin |first1=John |last2=Hill |first2=Benson Earle |title=Monthly Magazine and British Register |date=1804 |publisher=R. Phillips |page=270 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2yYxAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA270 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe son of the first marriage was Charles Wicksted Ethelston (1798\u20131872), a cleric who succeeded his father at Cheetham as a [[perpetual curate]], and was then incumbent at [[Uplyme]] in Devon. He married in 1822 Anne Peel, daughter of Robert Peel, of Wallington Hall, Norfolk.<ref>{{acad|id=ETLN818CW|name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted}}</ref> The second daughter Ellen Mary married in 1847 [[Charles Joseph Parke]];<ref>{{cite book |last1=critic |first1=Court magazine and monthly |title=The Court magazine and belle assembl\u00e9e [afterw.] and monthly critic and the Lady's magazine and museum |page=28 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4kAFAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA5-PA28 |language=en}}</ref> the youngest daughter Margaret Emily married [[John Perry-Watlington]] in 1849.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine |date=1849 |publisher=E. Cave |page=688 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SbNOAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA688 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEdwards Ethelston (1805\u2013c.1868), eldest son of the second marriage, was a surgeon in Manchester; the Cambridge register entry of 1823 for Edwards gives his father's residence as \"Collis Smedley\", i.e. Smedley Hill now in [[Smedley, Manchester]].<ref>{{acad|id=ETLN823EE|name=Ethelston, Edwards}}</ref> Hart Ethelston, third son, was rector of St Mark's, Cheetham from 1831. The Oxford register entry of 1826 for him gives his father's residence as [[Ardwick]].<ref>{{alox2|title=Ethelston, Hart}}</ref> He married Elizabeth Peel, daughter of Edmund Peel of Church Bank.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland |date=1871 |publisher=Harrison |page=1068 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H65CAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1068 |language=en}}</ref> Edwin Ethelston, fourth son, married Julia Croal, daughter of the plantation owner [[John Croal]] in [[Demerara]].<ref name=\"BurkeLG\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland |date=1879 |publisher=Harrison |page=520 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R3YyY91Uqi0C&pg=PA520 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=John Croal 1789-1853 |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/41736 |website=www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethelston, Charles}}\n[[Category:1767 births]]\n[[Category:1830 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Magistrates]]\n[[Category:English poets]]\n[[Category:People from Manchester]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:The political house that Jack built (1819) (14750648056).jpg|thumb|Political caricature from 1819, the central figure with the staff intended as Charles Ethelston]]\n'''Charles Wickstead Ethelston''', also given as '''Wicksted''' (1767\u20131830) was an English cleric, now remembered for the part he played in his role as magistrate on 16 August 1819, ahead of the [[Peterloo massacre]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the son of the Rev. Charles Ethelstone (1731\u20131795), an Oxford graduate, and his wife Margaret Hart (died 1803) of [[Salford]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Admission Register of the Manchester School |publisher=Manchester University Press |pages=4-5 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HAYNAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA4 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Ethelstone, Charles}}</ref><ref>{{CCEd |type=person |id=26866 |name=Ethelstone, Charles |year1=1754 |year2=1795 |accessed=18 March 2020}}</ref> He was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]] under Charles Lawson, and matriculated at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] in 1787, graduating B.A. in 1790 and M.A. in 1793.<ref name=\"acad\">{{acad|id=ETLN785CW|name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted}}</ref> He was known also by the surnames Ethelstone and Ethelstane.\n\nEthelston became a curate in 1794 at St Mark's Chapel, [[Cheetham Hill]], which was then an urbanising area adjacent to Manchester and [[Salford]].<ref name=\"CCEd\">{{CCEd |type=person |id=168787 |name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted |year1=1790 |year2=1831 |accessed=18 March 2020 }}</ref> His father, who died the following year, had recently completed it, at his own expense, on the Shooting Butts field at Cheetham;<ref name=\"Stancliffe\">{{cite book |last1=Stancliffe |first1=F. S. |title=The Manchester Royal Eye Hospital |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=5 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cRgNAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA5 |language=en}}</ref> it was a [[chapel of ease]] between the [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Prestwich]] and [[Manchester Collegiate Church]], for which Charles Ethelstone the elder had permission to build in 1790, in a hamlet where cotton merchants lived.<ref name=\"Genuki\">{{cite book |title=Genuki: St Mark Church of England, Cheetham, Lancashire |url=https://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Cheetham/StMark |language=en}}</ref> The chapel was consecrated on 24 July 1794 by [[William Markham]].<ref name=\"Churches\">{{cite web |title=Lancashire OnLine Parish Clerk Project |url=https://www.lan-opc.org.uk/Manchester/Cheetham/churches.html |website=www.lan-opc.org.uk}}</ref> Later, Ethelston became a [[perpetual curate]] there. A Jubilee School was built in Cheetham, and a plot of land obtained from [[Thomas Reynolds-Moreton, 1st Earl of Ducie|Lord Ducie]] to build a church to seat 1500.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lewis |first1=Samuel |title=A Topographical Dictionary of England: Comprising the Several Counties, Cities, Boroughs, Corporate and Market Towns, Parishes, Chapelries, and Townships, and the Islands of Guernsey, Jersey, and Man, with Historical and Statistical Descriptions|date=1840 |publisher=S. Lewis & Company |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iARBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA501 |language=en}}</ref> The church was closed in 1982, and demolished around 1998.<ref name=\"Genuki\"/><ref name=\"Churches\"/>\n\nIn 1801, Ethelston was made rector of [[Worthenbury]], near [[Wrexham]].<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> The presentation was presumably (according to [[Francis Robert Raines]]) by [[Sir Richard Price Puleston, 1st Baronet]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chetham Society |first1=Manchester |title=Remains, historical and literary, connected with the palatine counties of Lancaster and Chester. New ser |date=1883 |publisher=Manchester |page=307 |url=https://archive.org/details/remainshistornew23chetuoft/page/306/mode/2up}}</ref> In 1804 he became a Fellow of Manchester Collegiate Church.<ref name=\"acad\"/>\n[[File:St Mark's Church, Cheetham Hill, 1891.jpg|thumb|St Mark's Church, Cheetham Hill, interior in 1891]]\n\n==Civic Manchester==\nEthelston was chaplain to Silvester's Volunteers, raised in 1803 by John Silvester.<ref name=\"Navickas\">{{cite book |last1=Navickas |first1=Katrina |title=Loyalism and Radicalism in Lancashire, 1798-1815 |date=2009 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-955967-1 |page=121 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xYUDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA121 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Timperley |first1=Charles Henry |title=Records historical, municipal |date=1874 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YA4HAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA67 |language=en}}</ref> Silvester was a millowner and magistrate, and the volunteer unit, the 2nd Regiment of the Manchester and Salford Rifle Volunteers, was active against [[Luddites]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Philp |first1=Mark |title=Resisting Napoleon: The British Response to the Threat of Invasion, 1797\u20131815 |date=2016 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-351-90385-1 |page=65 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DamoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT65 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nFor the Golden Jubilee of [[George III]], celebrated on 25 October 1809, Ethelston addressed in the Collegiate Church John Ratliff the boroughreeve and his constables, joined by the Masonic Lodge and the Orange Order. There was a procession on to [[St Ann's Square, Manchester|St Ann's Square]], joyshots from dragoons and a volley from the rifle brigade. A loyal toast was drunk, and dinner for around 250 eaten at the [[Manchester Cotton Exchange]]. Nearly 800 children from the [[Lancasterian school]] lined Lever Street.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Tradesman |date=1809 |pages=532-533 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9C4aAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA532 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812, Ethelston and Silvester were among a group of loyalists intending to hold a dinner in the Exchange, with a toast and pledge to the [[Prince Regent]]. It was frustrated by an occupation of the Exchange, that led to vandalism.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Phythian |first1=Graham |title=Peterloo: Voices, Sabres and Silence |date=2018 |publisher=History Press |isbn=978-0-7509-8951-0 |page=46 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hA5dDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT46 |language=en}}</ref> In 1814 Ethelston was a founding board member of [[Manchester Royal Eye Hospital]].<ref name=\"Stancliffe\"/>\n\n==Magistrate==\nClerical magistrates were common in England in the later 18th century and early 19th century. Their numbers dropped back after 1832 and the [[Great Reform Act]]: in 1740 they were uncommon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hole |first1=Robert |title=Pulpits, Politics and Public Order in England, 1760-1832 |date=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-89365-7 |edition=186 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8du3_4Q5V8AC&pg=PA186 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibson |first1=William |title=Church, State and Society, 1760\u20131850 |date=1994 |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education |isbn=978-1-349-23204-8 |page=13 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkpdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13 |language=en}}</ref> In [[Lancashire]] the custom was to exclude manufacturers from the bench, to keep it impartial in trade disputes: the practical result was that it was dominated by landowners and clerics, and by [[High Church]] and [[High Tory]] views. In Manchester at this period the prominent magistrates, according to Marlow, were the lawyer [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]], and two clerics, Ethelston and William Robert Hay.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |page=49 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs a magistrate, Ethelston employed informers and spies, passing information about possible subversion to the [[Home Office]]. The Home Office funded spies in industrial districts: for Ethelston and Hay, and also Ralph Fletcher, magistrate at [[Bolton]], John Lloyd who was a magistrate's clerk at [[Stockport]], and Henry Enfield, town clerk of [[Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The Town Labourer, 1760-1832; the new civilization |date=1917 |publisher=London, Longmans, Green |page=258|volume=1 |url=https://archive.org/details/townlabourer00hammuoft/page/258/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Turner |first1=Bernadette |title=A Loyal Englishman?: John Lloyd and Aspects of Oath-taking in 1812 |url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1057/9780230509382_9 |website=Radicalism and Revolution in Britain, 1775\u20131848: Essays in Honour of Malcolm I. Thomis |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK |pages=133\u2013142 |language=en |doi=10.1057/9780230509382_9 |date=2000}}</ref> In 1816 Ethelston was encouraged by [[John Hiley Addington]], at the Home Office as parliamentary secretary to his brother [[Lord Sidmouth]], to employ spies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Reid |first1=Robert |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=2017 |publisher=Random House |isbn=978-1-4735-5477-1 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QBcqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT45 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Riding |first1=Jacqueline |title=Peterloo: The Story of the Manchester Massacre |date=2018 |publisher=Head of Zeus Ltd |isbn=978-1-78669-582-6 |page=69 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ydVADwAAQBAJ&pg=PT69 |language=en}}</ref> Ethelston, Fletcher and Hay had in common membership of the [[Loyal Orange Institution]].<ref name=\"Navickas\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Neal |first1=Frank |title=Sectarian Violence: The Liverpool Experience, 1819-1914 : an Aspect of Anglo-Irish History |date=1988 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-1483-3 |page=19 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EqfnAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA19 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nEthelston had some success in 1817, when he sent Samuel Fleming and another spy into Yorkshire, to look for [[pike (weapon)|pike]]s being stored.<ref name=\"Hammonds\">{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The Town Labourer, 1760-1832; the new civilization |date=1917 |publisher=London, Longmans, Green |pages=260-261 |url=https://archive.org/details/townlabourer00hammuoft/page/260/mode/2up}}</ref> Fleming was an Irish weaver who had served in Silvester's Volunteers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Michael T. |last2=Macleod |first2=Emma |last3=Pentland |first3=Gordon |title=Political Trials in an Age of Revolutions: Britain and the North Atlantic, 1793\u20141848 |date=2018 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-3-319-98959-4 |page=198 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j_CBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA198 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1818 Ethelston clashed with and abused Thomas Chapman, proprietor of the ''[[Manchester Observer]]'', at a vestry meeting of the Manchester parish. Chapman was concerned with the oversight of the accounts of the local constables.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=The Manchester Observer: Biography of a Radical Newspaper |journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library |date=1 March 2019 |volume=95 |issue=1 |pages=31\u2013123, at pp. 46-47 |doi=10.7227/BJRL.95.1.3 |url=http://clok.uclan.ac.uk/28037/1/28037.pdf}}</ref> In 1818 also, during the weavers' strike, the magistrates Ethelston, Norris, William Marriott, and Ralph Wright pre-empted a planned meeting of weavers on 4 September, at Ashton Cross, [[Tameside]], with a notice that such assemblies of the unemployed were a danger to the public peace.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The skilled labourer, 1760-1832 |date=1919 |publisher=London, New York [etc.] : Longmans, Green and co. |page=116 |url=https://archive.org/details/skilledlabourer00hammiala/page/116/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n===Events of 1819===\nSubsequently Ethelston's credibility with the Home Office dropped. He wrote to Lord Sidmouth in June 1819 of an intended \"general rising\".<ref>Robert Poole, \"By the Law or the Sword\": Peterloo Revisited'', History Vol. 91, No. 2 (302) (April 2006), pp. 254\u2013276, at p. 265\u2013266. Published by: Wiley {{jstor|24427836}}</ref> Fleming had fed him a report that [[William Cobbett]]'s visit to Lancashire was the signal for such a rising.<ref name=\"Hammonds\"/> His spy John Livesey tried to make direct contact with Sidmouth in London during 1819, claiming Ethelston had directed him to do so.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bend |first1=Nathan Ashley |title=The Home Office and Public Disturbance, c.1800-1832 |date=2018 |pge=105 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/27d9/3b2be3a1cb1820c00927156e5d56a60dd0b1.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Making of the English Working Class]]'', [[E. P. Thompson]] wrote of summer 1819 that \"The government wanted blood \u2014 not a holocaust, but enough to make an example.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=Edward Palmer |title=The Making of the English Working Class |date=1980 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0140136037 |page=723 |language=en}}</ref> In the historiography of Peterloo, however, Thompson's thesis from 1963, in the form that the Home Office deliberately triggered violence against the meeting in [[St Peter's Square, Manchester|St Peter's Field]], has been challenged.<ref name=\"Read\">Donald Read, ''Reviewed Work: Peterloo: The Case Reopened by Robert Walmsley'', History Vol. 55, No. 183 (1970), pp. 138\u2013140. Published by: Wiley {{jstor|24406795}}</ref> \n\nCorrespondence of the Home Office with Lancashire magistrates was through [[Henry Hobhouse (archivist)|Henry Hobhouse]], under-secretary of state from 1817 to 1827. He made it clear that the magistrates should set their house in order. In January 1819 he used a phrase about blood \"shed either by the Law or the sword\", prompted by a letter from Ralph Fletcher.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: The English Uprising |date=2019 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-878346-6 |page=211 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q5ygDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA211 |language=en}}</ref> On 23 July the Select Committee of Lancashire and Cheshire Magistrates was formed, and its first act was to lay a case of [[seditious libel]] against [[James Wroe]], editor of the ''Manchester Observer''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |page=111 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===16 August 1819, Peterloo===\n{{main|Peterloo Massacre}}\nThe magistrates most involved with Peterloo were Ethelston, Hay, Hulton and Norris.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Read |first1=Donald |title=Peterloo The Masssacre and its Background |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=75 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JMVRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA75 |language=en}}</ref> The roles of both Ethelston, reader of the [[Riot Act]], and [[William Hulton]] who brought in the militia, were later questioned as part of revisionism applied to Thompson's account.<ref name=\"Read\"/> Marlow argues that the invocation of the Riot Act was a side-issue, the magistrates having power in [[common law]] to disperse crowds.<ref name=\"Marlow\">{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |pages=147\u2013148 |language=en}}</ref>\n \nThe four were present, and Hulton chaired the committee of magistrates. From around 11 am, a group of nearly a dozen Lancashire and Cheshire magistrates were at Edmund Buxton's house on Mount Steet, overlooking St Peter's Field. It included also Ralph Fletcher, William Marriott, John Silvester and Ralph Wright.<ref>Others being the Rev. John Holdsworth Mallory, Robert Fielden, and Thomas Willian Tatton. ''The Tories, and their punishment of the people at the Peterloo meeting: a few words addressed to working men, the electors of Manchester and elsewhere, as to their duty.'' 1868, at p. 5. {{jstor|60216487}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Stanley |first1=Edward |title=Three Accounts of Peterloo |date=2015 |publisher=Manchester University Press |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sHq7AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA3 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe radicals' meeting on St Peter's Field began at 1.40 pm, as [[Henry Hunt (politician)|Henry Hunt]] started to speak. Hulton's committee took two decisions: to arrest leading radicals; and to disperse the crowd. The stentorian Ethelston read the Riot Act from a window in the Mount Street house, at a point between the attempted enforcements of those decisions. Hay gave an account of how Ethelson hung out of the window, and he had stood behind, ready to catch the tails of Ethelston's coat if he had started to topple. It is not clear that Ethelston was heard. Silvester then left the house, and read the Riot Act from a card.<ref name=\"Marlow\"/>\n\nIn the film ''[[Peterloo (film)|Peterloo]]'' by [[Mike Leigh]], Ethelston is played by [[Vincent Franklin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Peterloo (2018) - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4614612/fullcredits}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath of Peterloo===\n[[File:The political house that Jack built (1819) (14587018178).jpg|thumb|left|Caricature of a two-faced clerical magistrate, from 1819, with the right-hand part holding gallows, scourge, blunderbuss and shackles.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hone |first1=William |title=Regency Radical: Selected Writings of William Hone |date=2003 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=978-0-8143-3060-9 |page=423 note 21 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=52XRU9KuL9kC&pg=PA423 |language=en}}</ref>]] \nSome days afterwards, according to a letter published in the ''Manchester Observer'', Ethelston said while preaching that  Peterloo was the will of God.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=426 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA426 |language=en}}</ref> Henry Hunt appeared before the magistrates on 20 August, initially charged with [[high treason]], those on the bench being Sir William Bagshawe, [[John Byng, 1st Earl of Strafford|Sir John Byng]], Ethelston, Ralph Fletcher, William Hulton, William Marriott, James Norris as chairman, Thomas William Tatton, Trafford Trafford, J. Watkins and Richard Wright.<ref>{{cite book |title=Peterloo Massacre, Containing a Faithful Narrative of the Events which Preceded, Accompanied, and Followed the Fatal Sixteenth of August, 1819, on the Area Near St. Peter's Church, Manchester, Including the Proceedings which Took Place at the Inquest at Oldham ... to which is Added, an Accurate List of the Names and Places of Residence of Those who Were Killed, Wounded and Maimed |date=1819 |publisher=publisher not identified |page=28 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AP4xAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA28 |language=en}}</ref> Ethelston became concerned with headgear: radical supporters were wearing white hats, in imitation ofHunt, with green ribbons, and he wrote to Sidmouth about it on 13 September.<ref>James Epstein, ''Understanding the Cap of Liberty: Symbolic Practice and Social Conflict in Early Nineteenth-Century England'', Past & Present No. 122 (Feb., 1989), pp. 75\u2013118, at p. 110. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650952}}</ref>\n\nEthelston defended William Robert Hay in the ''[[Manchester Gazette]]'' on 25 September 1819, complaining of the ''[[ad hominem]]'' attacks made on all those who opposed reformers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=428 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA428 |language=en}}</ref> [[William Benbow]] in his ''Rambler's Magazine'' in 1822 listed \"Hay and Ethelstone\" with disreputable clerics as \"chief agitators\" in Manchester.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Rambler's Magazine: Or, Fashionable Emporium of Polite Literature|date=1822 |publisher=Benbow |page=409 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=r103AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA409 |language=en}}</ref> Satire against clerical magistrates picked on Ethelston.<ref>{{cite book |page=69 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5PiADwAAQBAJ&pg=PA69}}</ref> According to Gibson, \"It took many years for the people to forget that the magistrates who read the Riot Act at the Peterloo d\u00e9b\u00e2cle were Anglican clergy.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibson |first1=William |title=Church, State and Society, 1760\u20131850 |date=1994 |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education |isbn=978-1-349-23204-8 |pages=88-89 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkpdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA88 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Henry Grey Bennet]] asked the radical [[John Shuttleworth (industrialist)|John Shuttleworth]] on 18 November 1819 for information about the magistrates who signed the warrant to arrest Henry Hunt. This request may have prompted the pamphlet ''Manchester Slaughter!'' by \"Old Radical\". It took the form of an unsympathetic review of Ethelston's book of verse from 1803.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=426 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA426 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA significant publication and best-seller of November 1819 was ''The Political House that Jack Built'', a 24-page verse pamphlet parody of ''[[This Is the House That Jack Built]]'', by [[William Hone]], illustrated by [[George Cruikshank]]'s woodcut caricatures.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Ben |title=The Laughter of Triumph: William Hone and the Fight for the Free Press |date=2014 |publisher=Faber & Faber |isbn=978-0-571-31721-9 |pages=289-290 |language=en}}</ref> It contained \"The Clerical Magistrate\" with lines\n\n<poem>If the People were legally Meeting, in quiet\nWould pronouce it, decidedly\u2014''sec. Stat''\u2014a Riot,\nAnd order the Soldiers 'to aid and assist',\nThat is\u2014kill the helpless, who cannot resist.</poem>\n\nThe accompanying cut by Cruikshank is based on Ethelston, and contains internal references to the way Cruikshank depicted [[Lord Castlereagh]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gardner |first1=J. |title=Poetry and Popular Protest: Peterloo, Cato Street and the Queen Caroline Controversy |date=2011 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-0-230-30737-7 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=P-eHDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA57 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Patten |first1=Robert L. |title=George Cruikshank's Life, Times, and Art: 1792-1835 |date=1992 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |isbn=978-0-7188-2872-1 |page=162|volume=1 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Last years==\nEthelston suffered a head injury when the horse of his [[gig (carriage)|gig]] ran away. He resided at addresses west and north of Manchester (see under Family). He died in September 1830, at age 63, and was buried at St Mark's, Cheetham Hill.<ref name=\"acad\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=428 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA428 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''The Suicide with Other Poems'' (1803)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ethelston |first1=Charles Wicksted |title=The Suicide with Other Poems |date=1803 |publisher=Author and Published |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MfY_AQAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Address delivered in the Exchange Room, in Manchester, to a General Meeting convened by the Boroughreeve and Constables, on Wednesday the 11th. of Decr.,1811, for the purpose of Taking into Consideration the Expediency of Founding Schools on the Plan of Dr. Bell'' (Manchester, 1811), against the [[Lancasterian system]].\n*''The Unity of the Church'' (1814), sermon.<ref name=\"Chetham\">{{cite book |last1=Radcliffe |first1=John |last2=Greswell |first2=William Parr |last3=Jones |first3=Thomas |last4=Byrom |first4=John |title=Bibliotheca Chethamensis. Sive Bibliothec\u00e6 Public\u00e6 Mancuniensis ab Humfredo Chetham armigero fundat\u00e6 catalogus exhibens libros in varias classes pro varietate argumenti distributos ... |date=1883|volume=VI |publisher=Mancunii : Excudebat J. Harrop, etc. |pages=118-119 |url=https://archive.org/details/b29004470_0002/page/118/mode/2up/}}</ref> It was attacked by the [[Wesleyan Methodist]] apologist Edward Wesley Hare (1774\u20131818), writing from Liverpool in 1815, in ''The Exclusive Claims of Episcopal Ordination Examined and Rejected'' (1815);<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hare |first1=Edward Wesley |title=The exclusive claims of episcopal ordination examined and rejected, and the Methodist ministry vindicated; in a ser. of letters to C.W. Ethelson: being a reply to his sermon on 'The unity of the Church'. |date=1815 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QTRcAAAAQAAJ |language=en}}</ref> he had been on the Manchester circuit in 1813.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Joseph |title=Hall's circuits and ministers: an alphabetical list of the circuits in Great Britain, with the names of the ministers stationed in each circuit, from 1765 to 1885 : with appendix from 1886-1896 |date=1897 |page=208 |url=https://archive.org/details/28455030.1897.emory.edu/page/n209/mode/2up |language=English}}</ref> Ethelston was defended in the anonymous ''Strictures on Hare's Letters to the Rev. C. Ethelston'' (1815), <ref>{{cite book |title=Strictures on Hare's Letters to the Rev. C. Ethelston, and on the Methodistical Schism, etc |date=1815 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NmljAAAAcAAJ |language=en}}</ref> and Hare returned to the subject in ''A Further Vindication of the Methodist Ministry'' (1816).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hare |first1=Edward Wesley |title=A further vindication of the Methodist Ministry, against the exclusive claims of Episcopal Ordination: in a series of letters, addressed to ... C. W. Ethelston ... occasioned by anonymous strictures on the author's former letters [to him in answer to his sermon on the Unity of the Church], etc |date=1816 |publisher=Roberts & Company |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UQZgAAAAcAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n*''A Patriotic Appeal to the Good Sense of All Parties'' (1817), pseudonymous, as \"An Anti-Jacobin\".<ref name=\"Chetham\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Dicitonary of Anonymous and Pseudonymous English Literature |publisher=Ardent Media |page=312 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Tg0caI1-EToC&pg=PA312 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nEthelston was twice married: firstly to Mary Threlfall, daughter of John Threlfall of [[Chorley]]; and secondly in 1804 to Hannah Edwards, daughter of John Edwards of [[Kelsterton]].<ref name=\"acad\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Aikin |first1=John |last2=Hill |first2=Benson Earle |title=Monthly Magazine and British Register |date=1804 |publisher=R. Phillips |page=270 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2yYxAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA270 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe son of the first marriage was Charles Wicksted Ethelston (1798\u20131872), a cleric who succeeded his father at Cheetham as a [[perpetual curate]], and was then incumbent at [[Uplyme]] in Devon. He married in 1822 Anne Peel, daughter of Robert Peel, of Wallington Hall, Norfolk.<ref>{{acad|id=ETLN818CW|name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted}}</ref> The second daughter Ellen Mary married in 1847 [[Charles Joseph Parke]];<ref>{{cite book |last1=critic |first1=Court magazine and monthly |title=The Court magazine and belle assembl\u00e9e [afterw.] and monthly critic and the Lady's magazine and museum |page=28 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4kAFAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA5-PA28 |language=en}}</ref> the youngest daughter Margaret Emily married [[John Perry-Watlington]] in 1849.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine |date=1849 |publisher=E. Cave |page=688 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SbNOAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA688 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEdwards Ethelston (1805\u2013c.1868), eldest son of the second marriage, was a surgeon in Manchester; the Cambridge register entry of 1823 for Edwards gives his father's residence as \"Collis Smedley\", i.e. Smedley Hill now in [[Smedley, Manchester]].<ref>{{acad|id=ETLN823EE|name=Ethelston, Edwards}}</ref> Hart Ethelston, third son, was rector of St Mark's, Cheetham from 1831. The Oxford register entry of 1826 for him gives his father's residence as [[Ardwick]].<ref>{{alox2|title=Ethelston, Hart}}</ref> He married Elizabeth Peel, daughter of Edmund Peel of Church Bank.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland |date=1871 |publisher=Harrison |page=1068 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H65CAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1068 |language=en}}</ref> Edwin Ethelston, fourth son, married Julia Croal, daughter of the plantation owner [[John Croal]] in [[Demerara]].<ref name=\"BurkeLG\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland |date=1879 |publisher=Harrison |page=520 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R3YyY91Uqi0C&pg=PA520 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=John Croal 1789-1853 |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/41736 |website=www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethelston, Charles}}\n[[Category:1767 births]]\n[[Category:1830 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Magistrates]]\n[[Category:English poets]]\n[[Category:People from Manchester]]\n", "name_user": "Charles Matthews", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAftermath of Peterloo:fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Ethelston"}
